[normal]The factors responsible for white working class pupils’ [bold]educational underachievement, including the impact of home and family.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.
[normal] 
[normal]We are convinced that factors in families and communities have a significant impact on patterns of educational achievement from Early Years onwards.
[normal] 
[normal]2.2. 
[normal]The research
[normal] published in 
[normal]A Long Division
[normal] (IPPR 2012)
[normal] and elsewhere showing that schools can make 20% difference to narrowing gaps but that factors outside school lead to 80% of any gaps in achievement. In projects such as th
[normal]e Aylesbury Standards Project (
[normal]ASPIRE) and 
[normal]interventions in Chesham, we are also working to develop family and community support for learners. 
[normal]2.3. 
[normal]We would not want to generalise about the factors in families and communities that lie behind the impact of families and communities on the achievemen
[normal]t of white working class children. 
[normal]Organisations
[normal] such as The Roundtree trust and researchers such as Steve Strand have explored this issue. 
[normal]We would also commend the background papers supporting the 2013 Ofsted 
[normal]Unseen Child
[normal] particularly 
[normal]the paper
[normal] by Dennis
[normal] Mongon, 
[normal]Educational Attainment: White British Students from Low Income Backgrounds
[normal] (DfE 2013).
[normal]2.4. Mongon identifies school interventions that make a difference:
[normal]We are using these three areas a
[normal]s
[normal] cornerstones of our work to raise achievement for white working class and other underachieving groups.
[normal]2.5.i  Discussions with Secondary Headteachers have recommended that consideration is given to th
[normal]e different challenges for rural and urban students from a white working class background. The impact of relative deprivation by comparison with the community you live with is distinct from being member of a community where a larger number are from a simil
[normal]ar social and economic context. This can be ,manifest in a more significant lack of aspiration and less experience of, and belief in,  the possibility and potential of social mobility. 
[normal]2.5.ii. School leaders felt that we do not know enough about the impac
[normal]t of social change on rural white working class learners. More needs to be done to understand the effect of changes in the ethnic 
[normal]make-up of rural communities and the increased success and prosperity of young people form ethnic minority backgrounds. There 
[normal]is a hypothesis that white working class communities  is a rural environment may be less well integrated into patterns of social change that are accepted in urban communities and, as a result, are less well equipped, and less positive about,  social or geo
[normal]graphical mobility
[normal]2.6. We
[normal] interviewed Headteachers from three
[normal] Aylesbury Primary schools 
[normal]which serve less advantaged communities
[normal]. In 2011/12 each of these schools
[normal] 
[normal]had
[normal] a
[normal]n
[normal] achievement gap for students eligible for FSM 
[normal]that wa
[normal]s 
[normal]both
[normal] 
[normal]narrower than
[normal] national or 
[normal]where this cohort achieve
[normal]d
[normal] more highly that other pupils in the school
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]They were unanimously of the
[normal] view that, as well as providing  a good quality of teaching and learning,  their success 
[normal]was the result of
[normal]  a strong and cohesive pastoral care system that
[normal] supp
[normal]orted
[normal] children
[normal] in such a way that they were ready to learn when they we
[normal]re in the classroom. 
[normal]2.7.i
[normal].
[normal] The importance of pastoral support was echoed by the secondary sector. Here it was argued that the achievement of all students from less advantaged backgrounds could be, and is
[normal], enhanced
[normal] by an on-going, targeted, evidence based focus on removing barriers 
[normal]to 
[normal]learning and
[normal] aspiration. 
[normal]2.7.ii. This would include a relentless focus on monitoring attendance, working in partnership with families, engaging with health professionals to support physical and mental health, with the police in targeting support for at
[normal] risk students and promoting restorative justice. 
[normal]2.8 It is our view that those working in education from the earliest years to the end of the secondary phase need to work to engage with families and communities, to know the families in the communities th
[normal]ey serve and to build powerful relationships.
[normal]2.9. It was felt that changes to the Ofsted framework over the last 18 months have reduced the significance and celebration of high quality pastoral care as a pre-requisite for student achievement, particularly
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] children and young people from less advantaged backgrounds.
