[normal]4)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What steps schools can take to improve the educational outcomes and attainmen[bold]t of white working class pupils?[bold]4.1. We are supporting and promoting the interventions championed
[normal] by the Sutton Trust, 
[normal]the Education Endowment fund
[normal] and 
[normal]in The
[normal] Unseen Child
[normal] report and 
[normal]its
[normal] supporting papers
[normal]. These are a key element of our strategies to ensure Pupil Premium has an impact on standards and on narrowing the gap
[normal] for all underachieving groups
[normal].
[normal]4.2. We also believe
[normal] that investing in good relationships with families and communities and strong pastoral care for children are key strategies.
[normal]4.3. We are convinced of the importance of early intervention and of coherent, joined up provision and collaboration between early
[normal] years, primary and secondary phases across communities. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The potential for a wider range of educational approaches, for example vocational pathways, to improve outcomes for white working class pupils.  [bold]5.1. 
[normal]An issue identified by schools and other educational professionals is the need for a greater celebration of a wider range of success and achievement. 
[normal]5.2
[normal]Currently, success is defined according to levels of educational achievement with a dis-
[normal]prop
[normal]o
[normal]rtionate
[normal] 
[normal]focus on access to selective universities. 
[normal]5.3.i. 
[normal]While we fully endorse and 
[normal]support attempts to raise aspirations and widen participation in further and higher education and selective universities we would also argue that developing a successful career o
[normal]r business or developing the skills required for manual or craft based work is equally important for a balanced society and a balanced economy. 
[normal]5.3.ii.
[normal] 
[normal]As such we would be supportive of any plans to raise the profile of apprenticeships and work based trai
[normal]ning that ensures young people are prepared both for a specific line of work but also have the independence, confidence and adaptability to change in response to evolution in the work place or changes in demand for skills.
